Azure Virtual Machines are on-demand, scalable computing resources that allow users to run operating systems and applications.

They support both Windows and Linux environments.

For example, a company can host its application backend on a VM.

# Real-Life Use Case:
A real-life use case is legacy application migration where apps cannot be containerized.

# Real-Life Example:
Another example is development environments where engineers need full OS control.

VMs provide flexibility and control in cloud computing.
